My husband made this for a dinner party this past weekend. Wow! It was fantastic. He left out the zucchini and added a few drops of hot sauce (Red Hot) It looked great and tasted even better.

Rating: 4
I had my doubts initially, but this is really good, and makes a lovely presentation. I followed the advice of other reviewers and left out the zucchini. I added a quarter teaspoon of ground cayenne, which I think was a successful addition, and I substituted finely ground white pepper for black pepper. I used frozen, homemade clam juice, which is a little more briny than the usual bottled stuff. Also used frozen, homemade shrimp stock instead of water. I tasted the soup shortly before adding it to the shrimp and bell peppers, and I was disappointed, but once all the elements are combined the finished soup is great. Will definitely make this again.

Rating: 3
Good, not great, too many veggies watered down the seafood flavor. Will make adjustments next time.

Rating: 4
I have made this almost every year at the holidays since it first appeared in the December 1998 issue of Bon Appetit. In my opinion, it is delicious as is and does not need hot sauce as other readers have mentioned. To shorten prep time I buy raw peeled and deveined shrimp that still have the tails on and then just cut the tails off to use in the broth (instead of buying shrimp with the whole shell in place and then having to remove it - takes too much time). This is one of my all-time favorite soups.

Rating: 4
I have now made this twice. It is just as good as the first time. It made a great starter/soup for Chritmas dinner of Prime rib. The presentation is wonderful. All guest will be clambering for the recipe.

Rating: 4
I followed the previous reviewer's advice and skipped the zucchini and added hot sauce. I also made a broth from crab shells and used this in place of the clam juice. The result was just excellent and my guests just raved about it.

